[Puck v0.13.0](https://github.com/measuredco/puck/releases/tag/v0.13.0) introduces some of our most powerful APIs yet,  enabling completely custom interfaces, adding support for object fields and mechanisms to restrict DropZones.

## TLDR

1. [**Custom interfaces**](https://puckeditor.com/docs/extending-puck/custom-interfaces): Take complete control of the Puck UI with the new custom interface APIs.
2. [**Object fields**](https://puckeditor.com/docs/api-reference/configuration/fields/object): Represent objects as fields with the new `object` field type.
3. [**DropZone restrictions**](https://puckeditor.com/docs/api-reference/components/drop-zone#allow): The new `allow` and `disallow` props allow you to restrict which components can be dropped into DropZones.
4. [**New plugin API (Breaking Change)**](https://puckeditor.com/docs/extending-puck/plugins): The plugin API has been updated to align with the new custom interfaces API. This is a breaking change. The plugin API remains experimental.
5. [**New transformProps API**](https://puckeditor.com/docs/integrating-puck/data-migration): The new transformProps API makes it easier to rename props on your components without breaking your payload.
6. [**New `ui` prop**](https://puckeditor.com/docs/api-reference/components/puck): Set the initial UI state for the Puck editor on render.
7. [**Add search to external fields**](https://puckeditor.com/docs/api-reference/configuration/fields/external#showsearch): Show a search input in the `external` field modal, enabling the user to query your external API.

## Highlights

### 🎨 Custom interfaces


It's now possible to create completely [custom Puck interfaces](https://puckeditor.com/docs/extending-puck/custom-interfaces) to integrate more deeply with your own UI and create a seamless experience for your users.

![custom-puck-ui-example](https://res.cloudinary.com/measuredco/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1734632203/puck/u6ihin6zmwlofmyhhwqf.jpg)

This can be achieved by passing children to the `<Puck>` component.

```tsx
import { Puck } from "@measured/puck";

export function Editor() {
  return (
    <Puck>
      <div style={{ background: "hotpink" }}>
        <Puck.Preview />
      </div>
    </Puck>
  );
}
```

See [this demo](https://demo.puckeditor.com/custom-ui/edit).

### 🪝 The `usePuck` hook

Access Puck's internals using the `usePuck` hook to extend Puck's functionality with powerful custom components.

```tsx
import { Puck, usePuck } from "@measured/puck";

const JSONRenderer = () => {
  const { appState } = usePuck();

  return <div>{JSON.stringify(appState.data)}</div>;
};

export function Editor() {
  return (
    <Puck>
      <JSONRenderer />
    </Puck>
  );
}
```

### 🗃️ Object fields

Object fields enable you to represent your `object` types with the fields API. No more flattening your props!

```tsx
const config = {
  components: {
    Example: {
      fields: {
        params: {
          type: "object",
          objectFields: {
            title: { type: "text" },
          },
        },
      },
      render: ({ params }) => {
        return <p>{params.title}</p>;
      },
    },
  },
};
```

### 🙅 DropZone restrictions

Restrict which components can be passed into a DropZone component with the [`allow` and `disallow` props](https://puckeditor.com/docs/api-reference/components/drop-zone#allow).

```tsx
const MyComponent = () => (
  <DropZone zone="my-content" allow={["HeadingBlock"]} />
);
```


