Finally, let’s add some classes to our **HeadingBlock** and remove the padding on the wrapper:

```tsx
    render: ({ title }) => (
      <div>
        <h1 className="text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-extrabold tracking-tight">
          {title}
        </h1>
      </div>
    ),
```

And our **Paragraph**:

```tsx
    render: ({ text, textAlign }) => (
      <div>
        <p style={{ textAlign }} className="leading-7 mt-6">
          {text}
        </p>
      </div>
    ),
```

Let’s see how that looks:

![Puck interface showing preview window with Tailwind for the HeadingBlock and Paragraph](https://res.cloudinary.com/measuredco/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1734628706/puck/tutorials/building-a-react-page-builder/screenshot_6_mgadve.jpg)

Great! The styles are rendering, but things are looking a little cramped.

## Rendering a custom root

To fix this, we’ll want to add a custom `root`. Puck allows us to change the default behaviour by overriding the `root` component of our page:

```tsx
export const config: Config<Props> = {
  ... existingConfig

  root: {
    render: ({ children }) => {
      return <div className="p-16">{children}</div>;
    },
  },
}
```

This time we’re using Tailwind instead of inline styles.

![Puck interface showing preview with additional padding wrapping the root of the preview](https://res.cloudinary.com/measuredco/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto/v1734628707/puck/tutorials/building-a-react-page-builder/screenshot_7_ayfbrc.jpg)

Much better!

## Taking it further

There are a bunch of Puck features that we won't cover in this tutorial that you could use to take your editor to the next level:

* **Adaptors** - allow your users to select content from an existing headless CMS using adaptors
* **Plugins** - the custom plugin API enables powerful new functionality. For example, the [`heading-analyzer`](https://github.com/measuredco/puck/tree/main/packages/plugin-heading-analyzer) plugin to analyse the document structure of your page and warn when you break WCAG2.1 guidelines
* **Custom fields** - create your own input types for your users, like calendar widgets

You'll find documentation on all of these via [our GitHub](https://github.com/measuredco/puck).

